## 🏆 Key Patterns for Success

### The React Compiler Advantage

Let the compiler optimize your code automatically:

```jsx
// Just write clean code - no manual optimization needed
function LeadsList({ leads, searchTerm }) {
const filteredLeads = leads.filter(lead =>
lead.name.toLowerCase().includes(searchTerm.toLowerCase())
)                                                          ;

return (
<div>
{filteredLeads.map(lead => (
<LeadCard key={lead.id} lead={lead} />
))}
</div>
)                                      ;
}
```

Only manually optimize expensive operations:

```jsx
// Keep useMemo for truly expensive calculations
const processedAnalytics = useMemo(() => {
return rawCallData
.filter(call => call.duration > 30)
.map(call => calculateSentimentScore(call.transcript))
.sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score)                     ;
}, [rawCallData])                                      ;
```

### Security Pattern (Non-Negotiable)

Every server action MUST authenticate:

```typescript
'use server';
import { currentUser } from '@clerk/nextjs/server';

export async function createLead(input: LeadInput) {
const user = await currentUser()                     ;
if (!user) throw new Error('Unauthorized');

return await db.insert(leads).values({
...input,
userId: user.id // CRITICAL: Always scope to user
})                                                ;
}
```

### Smart Data Loading

Use server components for initial data:

```typescript
// ✅ Server component loads data
export default async function LeadsPage() {
const leads = await getLeads()              ;
return <LeadsClient initialLeads={leads} /> ;
}

// ✅ Client component handles interactions
'use client';
export function LeadsClient({ initialLeads }) {
const [leads, setLeads] = useState(initialLeads) ;
// Interactive features here
}
```

### Background Tasks

Use Next.js `after` for non-blocking operations:

```typescript
import { unstable_after as after } from 'next/server';

export async function processCall(callId: string) {
const call = await updateCallStatus(callId, 'completed');

// These run after response is sent
after(async () => {
await generateTranscript(callId)     ;
await updateAnalytics(call.leadId)   ;
await sendFollowupEmail(call.leadId) ;
})                                   ;

return call ;
}
```

## What to do when things go wrong

- Run `bun filetree` to see the current file structure of the project (excludes node modules etc.)
- First, check the server and browser logs:
- Server Logs are continuously saved to `logs/server.log` file as they appear in the console. You can run `tail -n 200 server.log` for the latest logs of the current dev server session (the file is cleared each time before running `next dev`)
- Browser logs can be fetched by calling the `mcp_getConsoleLogs()` tool. If you can't access them, remind me to run `bun browser-mcp` in a terminal and `right click -> inspect` on the page to open Chrome Dev Tools (which connects the MCP server to the browser)
- If debugging type errors, run `bun check` after your changes to make sure everything works.
- If the problem could be related to a server side function that in any way interacts with the database, please try to use the `mcp_run_sql` tool from neon to interact with the db directly to understand the problem. After applying your changes, run the tool again to confirm that your solution has indeed worked.
- If I say "build error", you should run `bun run build` and fix any issues that you notice. Always run `bun run build` and confirm that the build was successful after your changes.
- I will often give you screenshots when something goes wrong with the UI. Try to "see" the UI through the photo and try to fix the design by looking at other components that might be visible / used in the page render. You should search and read as many components / pages / files as you need to so you understand the full context of the React render.
- If you can solve an issue using Next.js features vs using features of external packages, try using the Next.js solution because it is usually less error prone. This is not always the case as there might be popular javascript packages that solve issues in a simple way.
- Always run commands to figure out things - I will always give you permission to run almost any terminal command because I want you to read the output from the terminal directly. This results in a faster feedback loop. Feel free to add packages, remove files, or anything else through the terminal. I will give you permission.
- If you think searching the web is a good idea to look for docs or any other up to date information, just do it.

